TY  - JOUR
T1  - Using Adaptive Sparse Grids to Solve High-Dimensional Dynamic Models
AU  - Brumm, Johannes
AU  - Scheidegger, Simon
Y1  - 2017/09/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12216
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1575
EP  - 1612
VL  - 85
IS  - 5
KW  - Adaptive sparse grids
KW  - high-performance computing
KW  - international real business cycles
KW  - menu costs
KW  - occasionally binding constraints
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12216
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We present a flexible and scalable method for computing global solutions of high-dimensional stochastic dynamic models. Within a time iteration or value function iteration setup, we interpolate functions using an adaptive sparse grid algorithm. With increasing dimensions, sparse grids grow much more slowly than standard tensor product grids. Moreover, adaptivity adds a second layer of sparsity, as grid points are added only where they are most needed, for instance, in regions with steep gradients or at nondifferentiabilities. To further speed up the solution process, our implementation is fully hybrid parallel, combining distributed and shared memory parallelization paradigms, and thus permits an efficient use of high-performance computing architectures. To demonstrate the broad applicability of our method, we solve two very different types of dynamic models: first, high-dimensional international real business cycle models with capital adjustment costs and irreversible investment; second, multiproduct menu-cost models with temporary sales and economies of scope in price setting.
ER  - 

